### 🧩 The State Machine — Brain of the Robot

The robot doesn't use `delay()` anywhere in its main logic.
Instead it uses a **state machine** — a list of stages the
robot moves through one at a time.

```cpp
enum AutoState {
  AUTO_FORWARD,          // 🚗 Moving forward
  AUTO_OBSTACLE_BEEP,    // 🔔 Obstacle found — beep!
  AUTO_SCAN_LEFT,        // 👈 Servo turns left
  AUTO_SCAN_LEFT_WAIT,   // ⏳ Wait for servo to settle
  AUTO_READ_LEFT,        // 📏 Read left distance
  AUTO_SCAN_RIGHT,       // 👉 Servo turns right
  AUTO_SCAN_RIGHT_WAIT,  // ⏳ Wait for servo to settle
  AUTO_READ_RIGHT,       // 📏 Read right distance
  AUTO_CENTER_SERVO,     // ⬆️ Servo back to center
  AUTO_CENTER_WAIT,      // ⏳ Wait for center
  AUTO_DECIDE,           // 🧠 Which way to go?
  AUTO_REVERSE,          // ⬅️ Both blocked — go back
  AUTO_REVERSE_WAIT,     // ⏳ Wait while reversing
  AUTO_SCAN2_LEFT,       // 👈 Scan left again after reverse
  ...
  AUTO_TURN,             // 🔄 Turn toward open side
  AUTO_TURN_WAIT,        // ⏳ Wait while turning
  AUTO_CLEAR,            // 🚗 Move forward past obstacle
  AUTO_CLEAR_WAIT,       // ⏳ Wait while clearing
  AUTO_RESUME_CENTER,    // ⬆️ Center servo again
  AUTO_RESUME_CENTER_WAIT// ⏳ Wait then go back to AUTO_FORWARD
};
```

💡 **Why not use delay()?**
`delay()` freezes the entire Arduino. While waiting, it
can't read Bluetooth, can't update buzzer, can't do anything.
With a state machine — each state does ONE thing and returns
immediately. Everything runs in parallel smoothly.

